WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.060
We will study the development of the gastrointestinal tract

2
00:00:03.060 --> 00:00:06.020
and the peritoneal cavity and peritoneum

3
00:00:06.020 --> 00:00:11.140
in the developmental movement of the stomach, duodenum, intestine, and colon.

4
00:00:11.520 --> 00:00:16.820
We will begin by understanding it in the development of the stomach

5
00:00:16.820 --> 00:00:22.280
in relation to the liver, spleen, and

6
00:00:22.280 --> 00:00:22.720
pancreas.

7
00:00:23.240 --> 00:00:26.980
Let's understand the initial phase, what we call the delimitation of the embryo.

8
00:00:27.160 --> 00:00:28.000
We saw the integration.

9
00:00:28.071 --> 00:00:30.491
of this external coelom into an internal coelom.

10
00:00:30.891 --> 00:00:32.631
We arrive at this stage.

11
00:00:33.171 --> 00:00:36.411
And here, we see both in the sagittal view

12
00:00:36.411 --> 00:00:37.831
and in the transverse view.

13
00:00:38.011 --> 00:00:41.791
We clearly see the integration of my peritoneal cavity.

14
00:00:42.591 --> 00:00:44.611
Don't forget the synchronicity of development.

15
00:00:45.071 --> 00:04:47.551
One last image to see this integration.

16
00:00:49.251 --> 00:00:51.731
The main driver is growth,

17
00:00:52.111 --> 00:00:55.311
it's the formation of our cortex,

18
00:00:55.311 --> 00:00:55.971
but that's elsewhere.

19
00:00:56.142 --> 01:01:442
primitive, the overall growth of my embryo, the coiling and return

20
00:01:01.442 --> 00:01:02.482
to my midline.

21
00:01:02.482 --> 00:01:07.102
When you take a small baby, you hold it in your hands and it shows you

22
00:01:07.102 --> 00:01:11.202
the whole history of its embryology. You just have to follow the tissues. It's

23
00:01:11.202 --> 01:16:422
a three-dimensional movement in four and even in the fifth dimension.

24
00:01:16.782 --> 00:01:17.242
I mean

25
00:01:17.242 --> 01:22:622
by fourth dimension, time. The fifth dimension, I mean that it is this energetic,

26
00:01:22.622 --> 00:01:24.142
electrical component.

27
00:01:24.213 --> 00:01:26.833
overall that underlies the entire system.

28
00:01:27.533 --> 01:32:653
Don't forget that this movement is always integrated into this ascending phase

29
00:01:32.653 --> 00:01:33.593
of my ectoderm

30
00:01:33.593 --> 01:38:813
and relative descent of my endoderm, with this phase

31
00:01:38.813 --> 00:01:39.833
almost at the level of the heart.

32
00:01:40.513 --> 01:45:573
The ascent of the ectoderm and the descent of the endoderm and the integration of the

33
00:01:45.573 --> 00:01:45.973
heart

34
00:01:46.833 --> 01:52:153
stretch the primordia of the diaphragmatic musculature and those of the future muscles.

35
00:01:52.284 --> 01:57:364
This means that to treat and reorganize this entire space, you will need

36
01:57:364 --> 02:02:524
to understand that you will have to treat and release the diaphragm, because it is the one that will create

37
02:02:524 --> 02:05:284
this global delimitation.

38
02:05.544 --> 02:10:664
The ascent of my neural tube, the development of

39
02:10.664 --> 02:15:804
my peritoneal cavity, the placement of my heart is

40
02:15.804 --> 02:20.284
a movement that will reintegrate globally towards a point of attachment.

41
02:20.355 --> 02:24.755
which we call the umbilical cord. We could say that the umbilical cord,

42
02:24.935 --> 02:30.415
in its finality, contains the history of this development, of

43
02:30.415 --> 02:31.755
this unfolding, of

44
02:31.755 --> 02:36.135
this delimitation, of this reorganization of your peritoneum.

45
02:36.355 --> 02:42.235
This will integrate into specific rotational movements, organized in

46
02:42.235 --> 02:42.415
specific

47
02:42.415 --> 02:47.935
clockwise and counter-clockwise directions. On a frontal plane, we will see

48
02:47.935 --> 02:48.055
a

49
02:48.426 --> 02:53.526
global counter-clockwise developmental movement. On a transverse plane,

50
02:53.526 --> 02:55.566
we will see a clockwise

51
02:55.566 --> 03:00:886
developmental movement. This peritoneal cavity will begin to organize,

52
03:01.186 --> 03:01.986
to delimit itself.

53
03:02.446 --> 03:06.426
This means that it will move, and in this movement, you will have to learn to follow this

54
03:06.426 --> 03:11.466
development. First, there is the peritoneum that surrounds an organ. This

55
03:11.466 --> 03:14.006
is called a visceral peritoneum.

56
03:14.006 --> 03:16.126
When a peritoneum...

57
03:16.497 --> 03:18.517
connects an organ to the posterior

58
03:18.517 --> 03:20.217
part, it is called

59
03:20.217 --> 03:22.437
a mesentery. If it's the stomach,

60
03:22.577 --> 03:24.697
it will be called a mesogastrium.

61
03:24.857 --> 03:26.617
If it's the duodenum, it will be called

62
03:26.617 --> 03:28.557
the mesoduodenum. If it's

63
03:28.557 --> 03:30.637
a colon, it will be called the mesocolon.

64
03:30.837 --> 03:32.517
Or, depending on

65
03:32.517 --> 03:34.357
the location, it will be called

66
03:34.357 --> 03:36.777
a fascia of Tolte, for example.

67
03:37.057 --> 03:38.097
But if it's a

68
03:38.717 --> 03:40.797
small intestine, it's called

69
03:40.797 --> 03:42.857
a mesentery.

70
03:43.297 --> 03:44.437
Peritoneum that has the...

71
03:44.568 --> 03:50.128
Here, there is the posterior part, it is called the posterior parietal peritoneum.

72
03:50.988 --> 03:56.068
Laterally, it is called the lateral parietal peritoneum,

73
03:56.308 --> 03:59.328
the anterior parietal peritoneum.

74
03:59.668 --> 04:04:728
If it is a peritoneum that connects one organ to another organ, it

75
04:04:728 --> 04:07:048
is called an omentum.

76
04:07.248 --> 04:12.408
For example, you have the lesser omentum, which is a tissue that connects the liver to the stomach.

77
04:12.639 --> 04:15.499
You also have an omentum that connects the spleen to the stomach.

78
04:15.739 --> 04:21.159
An omentum, a mesentery, is always a double layer that carries

79
04:21.159 --> 04:23.319
a vessel right in the middle.

80
04:23.619 --> 04:29.299
But in the developmental movement, we will see that there will be folds and a reorganization

81
04:29.299 --> 04:34.419
that makes the omentum that is here, for example the mesentery, able to come to the side

82
04:34.419 --> 04:35.079
like this.

83
04:42.911 --> 04:48.131
And so here, there is a tissue that will attach and it will form an

84
04:48.131 --> 04:49.251
adhesion fascia.

85
04:49.451 --> 04:53.511
This is something that surgeons can resect without problem because there are no vessels.

86
04:53.771 --> 04:56.131
A mesentery always contains a vessel.

87
04:56.231 --> 05:00.491
Whereas a ligament or a fascia does not necessarily contain vessels.

88
05:00.591 --> 05:06.451
At the level of the peritoneum, we will have the mesoderm, the somatopleure, the splanchnopleure,

89
05:06.591 --> 05:08.711
the mesogastrium, ventral d'or...

90
05:09.442 --> 05:14.582
and we will have what are called mesenteries, fascias, omenta that we call

91
05:14.582 --> 05:17.002
epiploons or ligaments.

92
05:17.782 --> 05:22.822
All of that is the hyperperitoneum, we could say, initially organized in the peritoneal cavity, I

93
05:22.822 --> 05:23.062
mean.

94
05:24.102 --> 05:28.262
My intestine will start to grow, my liver will develop,

95
05:28.422 --> 05:32.382
my stomach wants to express itself, my lungs are growing.

96
05:32.582 --> 05:34.662
All of this needs to find its place.